\ul\b Non-Neutral Operations\ulnone\b0\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 Audio Fact Sheet p.782)\i0\par
\par
34.3.8 \b Clip fades\b0\par
When [Create Fades] on [Clip Edges] is enabled in the [Record/Warp/Launch Preferences], a short (up to 4 ms) fade is applied to the clip start and end to avoid clicks at the clip edges. These 'de-clicking' fades can also be applied to [Session View] clips via the [Clip Fade]  button. Additionally, [Arrangement View] clips have editable fades and crossfades. Applying any of these fade options is a non-neutral operation\par
\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 Audio Fact Sheet p.783)\par
\i0 34.3.9 \b Panning\b0\par
Live uses constant power panning with sinusoidal gain curves. Output is 0 dB at the center position and signals panned fully left or right will be increased by +3 dB. In order to minimize this volume change, it may be helpful to narrow the overall stereo width before doing extreme pan\'02ning. This can be done via the [Width] control in the [Utility] device.\par
\par
34.3.10 \b Grooves\b0\par
Under most conditions, playback of a warped clip that is at the same tempo as the [Set] is a neutral operation. However, if a groove  is applied, playback will be non-neutral at any tempo.\par
