\ul\b I/O and Routing Secrets!\par
\ulnone\b0\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Routing and I/O p.229)\par
\i0 15.5 \b Internal Routings\b0\par
Live's mixer and external routing devices allow for inter-track routings. These routings, albeit potentially confusing, enable many valuable creative and technical options. Via the mixer, inter\'02track routing can work two ways:\par
\par
\b 1.\b0  \ul Track A \ulnone is set up to \ul send\ulnone  its output signal to \ul Track B\ulnone . This is possible because every track that can receive an output signal of the appropriate type from Track A shows up in its [Output Type] chooser.\par
\par
\b 2.\b0  \ul Track B \ulnone is set up to \ul receive\ulnone  its input signal from \ul Track A\ulnone . This works because every track that delivers a signal of the appropriate type appears in Track B's [Input Type] chooser.\par
\par
\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Routing and I/O p.230)\par
\i0 Both approaches result in Track A's output being fed into Track B. \par
\par
\b Approach 1\b0  leaves Track B's in/out settings alone, and we can, at any time, add more tracks that feed their output into Track B. This is the method of choice for '\b many-to-one\b0 ' routings such as submixes or several MIDI tracks playing the same instrument.\par
In this scenario, soloing Track B will still allow you to hear the output of the tracks that are feeding it. Also, you can still solo Track A and hear its output signal. In this case, all other tracks are muted, including those that might also feed into Track B. Technically, what you hear is the output of Track B, with everything except Track A's signal removed.\par
\par
\b Approach 2\b0 , on the other hand, leaves Track A unaffected except for Track B tapping its output. We can easily add more tracks like Track B that all tap Track A's output. Instrument layering is a good example of such a \b 'one-to-many\b0 ' routing setup.\par
\par
\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Routing and I/O p.229)\i0\par
The 'Resampling' option in any audio track's [Input Type] chooser will route the Master output to that track. You can then decide on what exactly you will be resampling and mute, solo or other\'02wise adjust the tracks that are feeding the Master output. You will probably want to use the [Master Volume] meter to make sure that your level is as high as possible without clipping (indicated by red in the meter). Then you can arm the track and record into any of its empty clip slots. \par
\b\i Note:\b0  the recording track's own output will be suppressed while resampling is taking place, and will not be included in the recording.\i0\par
Samples created by resampling will be stored in with the current Set's Project folder, under Samples/Recorded. Until the Set is saved, they remain at the location specified by the Temporary Folder.\par
\par
\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Routing and I/O p. 232)\par
\i0 If a track has one or more [Instrument] or [Effect Racks] in its device chain, internal routing points (Pre FX, Post FX and Post Mixer) will also be available for every chain within the Rack. If a track contains one or more Drum Racks, internal routing points will be available for any of the Rack's return chains.\par
