\ul\b The Groove Pool\b0\par
\ulnone\i\par
(quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Using Grooves p.207)\i0\par
The [Groove Pool]'s controls work as follows:\par
\par
\b [Timing]\b0  adjusts how much the groove pattern will affect any clips which are using it.\par
\b [Random]\b0  adjusts how much random timing fluctuation will be applied to clips using the selected groove. At low levels, this can be useful for adding subtle 'humanization' to highly quantized, electronic loops.\par
\b\i Note: \b0 [ Random] applies differing randomization to every \ul\b voice\ulnone\b0  in your clip, so notes that originally occurred together will now be randomly offset both from the grid and from each other.\par
(quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Using Grooves p.208)\i0\par
\b [Velocity]\b0  adjusts how much the velocity of the notes in clips will be affected by the velocity information stored in the groove file.\par
\b\i Note:\b0  this slider goes from -100 to +100. i.e. At negative values, the effect of the groove's velocity will be reversed; loud notes will play \par
quietly and vice versa.\i0\par
\b [Global Amount]\b0  this parameter scales the overall intensity of [Timing], [Random] and [Velocity] for all of the available groove files. At 100%, the parameters will be applied at their as\'02signed values. \par
\b Note:\b0  the [Amount] slider goes up to 130%, which allows for even more exaggerated groove effects. If grooves are applied to clips in your Set, the Global Amount slider will also appear in Live's [Control Bar].\par
\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Using Grooves p.208)\i0\par
13.1.2 \b Committing Grooves\b0\par
Pressing the [Commit] button below the [Clip Groove] chooser 'writes' your groove parameters to the clip. For MIDI clips, this moves the notes accordingly. For audio clips, this creates [Warp Markers] at the appropriate positions in the clip.\par
After pressing Commit, the clip's [Groove] chooser selection is automatically set to [None]\par
\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Using Grooves p.210)\i0\par
13.3.1 \b Grooving a Single Voice\b0\par
Drummers will often use variations in the timing of particular instruments in order to create a convincing beat. For example, playing hi-hats in time but placing snare hits slightly behind the beat is a \{classic\} way of creating a laid-back feel. But because groove files apply to an entire clip at once, this kind of subtlety can be difficult to achieve with a single clip.\par
Provided your clip uses a [Drum] or [Instrument Rack], one solution can be to extract the chain (page 319) containing the voice that you want to independently groove. In this example, we'd extract the snare chain, creating a new clip and track that contained only the snare notes. Then we could apply a different groove to this new clip.\par
\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual)\par
\i0 13.3.2 \b Non-Destructive Quantization\b0\par
Grooves can be used to apply real-time, non-destructive quantization to clips. To do this, simply set the groove's [Timing],[Random] and [Velocity] amounts to 0% and adjust its [Quantize] and [Base] \par
parameters to taste. With only [Quantize] applied, the actual content of the groove is ignored, so this technique works the same regardless of which Groove file you use.\par
\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Using Grooves)\i0\par
13.3.3\b  Creating Texture With Randomization\b0\par
You can use a groove's [Random] parameter to create realistic doublings. This can be particu\'02larly useful when creating string textures from single voices. To do this, first duplicate the track \par
containing the clip that you want to 'thicken'. Then apply a groove to one of the clips and turn up its [Random] parameter. When you play the two clips together, each note will be slightly (and randomly) out of sync with its counterpart on the other track.\par
