\ul\b Launching Clips or Follow Actions\ulnone\b0\par
\par
14.7.1 \b Looping Parts of a Clip\b0\par
Let's say that you want to play a longer clip, but then you want only the last eight bars to loop. \par
You can set this up using Follow Actions:\par
\b 1. \b0 Drag the clip into the [Arrangement View] and make sure that the [Clip View]'s Loop switch is \ul not\ulnone  activated. Use the [Edit] menu's [Split] command  to split the clip between the \par
non-looping and looping parts:\par
\par
In the [Arrangement View]:\par
Splitting Clips\par
The [Split] command can divide a clip or isolate part of it.\par
To split a clip in two halves, do the following:\par
\b i.\b0  Unfold the track;\par
\b ii.\b0  In the waveform or MIDI display, click at the position where you want the clip to be split;\par
\b iii.\b0  Execute the [Split] command.\par
\par
To isolate a part of a clip, do the following:\par
\b i.\b0  Unfold the track;\par
\b ii.\b0  In the waveform or MIDI display, drag a selection over the part of the clip you want to \par
isolate;\par
\b iii.\b0  Execute the [Split] command to divide the original clip into three pieces.\par
\par
\par
\b 2.\b0  Click and drag the resulting two clips into the [Session View] by letting the mouse cursor hover over the [Session View] selector. Drop the two clips into a track. They now form a [Follow Action] group.\par
\par
\b 3.\b0  Set up Follow Actions for the first clip. You will want to make [Follow Action Time] equal to the clip's length. Set the [Follow Action A] chooser to 'Next', with a [Chance] setting of 100%, and set [Follow Action B] to \f1 '\f0 No Action'. Now this clip is set up to advance to the looping clip after it plays.\par
\par
\b 4.\b0  Activate the [Loop] switch for the second clip.\par
The first clip will now proceed to the second after it has played in its entirety; the second clip will simply play in a loop until it is stopped.\par
