\ul\b Computer Audio Resources and Strategies\par
\ulnone\b0\par
\i (quoting ableton live suite 11 Audio Fact Sheet p.783)\par
\i0 34.4 \b Tips for Achieving (and Abusing) Optimal Sound Quality in Live\par
\b0 *add* ?\par
\i\par
(quoting ableton live suite 11 user manual Working with Instruments and Effects p.281)\i0\par
Devices are turned on and off using their [Activator] switches. Turning a device off is like temporarily deleting it: The signal remains unprocessed, and the device does not consume CPU cycles. Live devices generally do not load down the CPU unless they are active.\par
\par
Note that no clipping can occur between devices because there is practically unlimited head\'02room. Clipping can occur when an overly strong signal is sent to a physical output or written to a \par
sample file.\par
\par
\b Strategies for Saving CPU Power\par
\b0 Real-time synthesis needs lots of computing power. However, there are strategies for reducing CPU load:\par
- When using warping, be aware that the Complex and Complex Pro modes use signifcantly more CPU power than the other Warp Modes.\par
- Turn off the any filters not needed.\par
- A filter's CPU cost correlates with the steepness of its slope - the 24 dB slope is more expensive than the 12 dB slope.\par
- Turn off any LFOs for a slightly positive influence on CPU.\par
- Stereo samples need significantly more CPU than mono samples, as they require twice the processing.\par
- Decrease the number of simultaneously allowed voices with the Voices control.\par
- Turn Spread to 0% if it is not needed.\par
- Any Interpolation and Antialias modes can also be turned off to conserve CPU resources.\par
